      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Why?\n\nThis is not surprising — the NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes) is specifically focused on **aqueous-phase** metal–ligand equilibria. Supercritical CO₂ is a very different medium:\n\n- **scCO₂** is a non-polar solvent used primarily in extraction and green chemistry applications. While metal-ligand complexation in scCO₂ has been studied (e.g., for nuclear waste processing with organophosphorus ligands or β-diketones), these data are typically found in specialized literature rather than in classical aqueous stability constant compilations.\n- Measuring thermodynamic stability constants in scCO₂ is experimentally challenging due to the high pressures involved and the lack of a well-defined ionic strength framework analogous to aqueous solutions.\n\nIf you're interested in metal complexation in scCO₂, I'd recommend searching journals like *The Journal of Supercritical Fluids* or *Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research* rather than aqueous equilibrium databases.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46*",
